The paper discusses the use of variational autoencoders (VAEs) for creating low dimensional representations of somatic mutation profiles, which is a common task in machine learning and falls under the category of deep learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of these representations for classification tasks, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also mentions the use of clustering and visualization, which are common tasks in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). Finally, the paper discusses the potential for data-driven models in precision oncology, which falls under the category of neural engineering (cs.NE).
